post_text:
The board would like to thank Brady Wachholz for his service, insight, and perspective while he has served as the School Board Student Representative. Brady has been a voice for students and the district on the board and his voice will be missed. Although he has been a non-voting member on the board, he has become a valued member of the school board team and the board appreciates his ideas, comments, and feedback.
The board hopes that his time as the Student Representative has sparked a desire for him to continue to explore public office and hopefully has enhanced his drive and passion for civic duty.
The board would like to wish Brady the best of luck on his senior year and all his future endeavors.

MEDIA CENTER PARAPROFESSIONAL – Central Public Schools

Date of Availability: 08/31/2020
Date Closing: Until Filled
Non-Licensed Position

Central Elementary School

MEDIA CENTER PARAPROFESSIONAL
6.25 hours per day
Anticipated Start Date: 8/31/2020

Responsibilities:
1. Supervise classes of students during media center time
2. Help students check out books and proficiently navigate the online book check out system
3. Shelve returned library books
4. Maintain a safe and orderly environment

Qualifications:
1. Ability to lift up to 50 pounds of weight
2. Ability to tolerate frequent bending and leaning.
3. High School Diploma
4. Possess basic academic competencies to provide tutorial assistance to the student(s) as needed
5. Experience with elementary age students preferred but not required

Salary and benefits in accord with master agreement

Apply online at: http://centralpublicschoolsmn.apptegy.us/o/central-public-schools/page/employment--524 by completing the district application, resume, cover letter, and letters of recommendation.

Head cook wanted!
Central Food Service and Taher, Inc. is looking for a head cook for the High School for the start of the 2020 school year.
Duties include preparing quality and safe entrees from the menu, unload and organize grocery items, clean and sanitize all equipment and surfaces used by the cook, help with monthly inventory and list groceries to order, to make the entrees. Previous experience in food service is preferred, but not required.
If interested, please contact Chantelle Eshleman, Central Food Service Director, at 952-467-7147 or email at ceshleman@isd108.org.

post_text:
Central Food Service is looking for Food Service Substitutes to help out as needed.
Substitutes work in most areas of the operation including food service prep, serving, dish room and clean up. Hours would vary, but generally would be from 8:30 a.m. to 1:30 p.m.
We are also looking for a Permanent Substitute Floater. A Permanent Floater does everything a Substitute does, but learns cashiering on top of the other duties. This position is guaranteed 2 days a week, but could be up to 5 days a week.
The hours on this are very flexible and you would have to be willing to come in as early as 6:30 one week, but maybe not until 10:00 another.
This position also goes until about 1:30 each day. Contact Chantelle Eshleman, Central Food Service Director at 952-467-7147 or email at
ceshleman@isd108.org.

Central Raiders Bus Service is looking for people interested in serving their community while having fun and making money.
Help the students in our district enjoy a safe, dependable ride to/from school and activities by signing on with Central Raiders Bus Service! We are currently looking to hire school bus & van drivers!

Flexible Hours -- Paid Training -- Signing Bonus – Referral Bonus
Possibility to bring your own kids with you!

Flexible Hours
Typical hours are 6:30-9:30 AM and 2:15-4:45 PM
Actual route times vary depending on the area covered.

Positions Available
Van driver
Bus route driver
Activities & field trip driver
Substitute bus and van driver

Requirements
Van driver- class D driver’s license
Bus driver- CDL w/ school bus & passenger endorsements
Don’t have one? We will pay you to train onsite!

SIGNING BONUS!
$800 signing bonus if you are licensed by the start of the school year.

Contact Jon Rumrill in the transportation office
Phone: 952-457-9324
Email: jon@fourpointo.com

Additionally, I am in football, trap shooting, and NHS.

High School Yearbook Announcement:

The Balfour-Taylor yearbook plant was closed due to the Covid 19 virus, however, it has reopened as of May 18 and they started printing yearbooks immediately.

At this time we don't know the exact date our books will be arriving, but sometime the beginning of July. When they arrive we will set up tables at the front of school to pick up your Yearbooks, students that have made deposits on their yearbooks can pay the balance at that time.

Central High school will send out an announcement for the date and time we will be set up at the front of school to pickup your yearbook.

Thank you,
Yearbook Staff, Brenda Messner

As the Minnesota Department of Education works closely with the Minnesota Department of Health to plan for the 2020-21 school year, we want to hear from families about their experience with the distance learning this spring.

shared_text:
Norwood Young America FFA
June 15 at 6:57 PM ·

Time to meet our chapter's 2020-21 Officer Team! First up is president Audrey Kamps! Here's what Audrey has to say:

I enjoy being in FFA because of all the great opportunities we are able to experience and because of all the new people we get to meet from around the state at different events.
One of my favorite things to do in FFA is show Guernseys at the Carver County Fair. I held the position of Vice President for the 2019-2020 school year, and I will be taking over the role as Chapter President for the 2020-2021 school year!
In October 2019, I organized a service project that went along with our annual corn drive. As a chapter, we packed and delivered lunches to the farmers in the fields and businesses in the area.
I love that FFA something for everyone, not just farmers, as some people might think. Whether you enjoy arranging flowers, judging animals, fixing machines, public speaking, etc., I’m sure we can find something you will enjoy!

post_text:
GREETINGS RAIDER NATION!

As you may know by now, we unfortunately will not be able to invite anyone other than immediate family to our graduation ceremony this year. However Central Public Schools will be broadcasting the graduation beginning at 5:45 PM on KLGB Radio (1310 AM/96.1 FM).

If you have friends and family that would like to listen to our graduation ceremony and live outside the radio play area, I would encourage you to download the KLGB App, which can be found at https://www.radio.net/s/kglb .

Additionally, we will be streaming the graduation ceremony live on our Raider Recap Facebook page. The link to the live feed can be found by using the following link:
https://www.facebook.com/norwoodcentralschools/?modal=admin_todo_tour

Please feel free to share this information with any extended family and friends that would like to attend our graduation ceremony at a distance.

As always, thank you so much for your support of our students and school

post_text:
Michael Foods out of Gaylord, MN contacted our city hall this week and shared that our area community (NYA, Cologne, Hamburg, Plato, New Germany) will be gifted FREE Food this Saturday, April 11th from 8am-10am.

Michael Food is a local restaurant distributor of egg and potato products. Due to the unforeseen circumstances of the COVID-19, they have an overabundance of product that needs to be given away. They have provided food shelves all throughout the state with their egg and potato products and now are distributing the remaining to area communities. Glencoe, Hutchinson and Gaylord have already participated and there are more to come in Arlington, New Ulm and others in addition to our community.

This event is OPEN TO ANYONE AND EVERYONE!!

The Hamburg Hawks, along with the Young America Cardinals, Cologne Hollanders and Norwood ballpark are gonna light it up tonight in honor of Central Public Schools!

Tonight at 8PM we will turn on the lights for 108 minutes (representing District 108) in support of the students, teachers and admin and their hard work and dedication during these difficult times.

Today would have been opening day for many of these student-athletes, and this is just one way for us to show our support and let them know we're thinking of them during this time.

We're all in this together. Stay home and look to the light!

#RAIDERPRIDE
#COMMUNITYPRIDE
#WEREALLINTHISTOGETHER
#STAYHOMESTAYSAFE

Central Schools is pleased to announce some exciting changes to our online presence. First, as of this morning, Central Public Schools has undergone an update to our website. The new web address is (www.isd108.org). Here you can find all the helpful information you did on our previous platform. If you have us bookmarked, please update your records.

Secondly, as part of our update, Central has developed an App. You can find it in the Google Play or Apple App store by searching "Central Public Schools ISD 108". This is everything Central in your pocket. Easily connect to your child's teacher, view lunch menus, and follow all the updates from Central Public Schools in one handy spot. Be looking for "specials" at Raider events by showing the app on your phone for free items.

post_text:
CONGRATULATIONS to the Central Speech Team for taking 3rd place at the meet in TCU on Saturday February 1, 2020.

Individual placements were as follows:

Middle School:
Abby Beltz got 3rd place in storytelling
Avery Lueck got 3rd place in poetry
Joe Docken got 6th place in Drama.

High school:
Wyatt Borst took 4th in humorous and Drew Castillo took 7th.
Brittany Buckentin took 6th in storytelling
Amy Wickenhouser took 5th in persuasive
Ellie Coffel took 6th in informative
Rubyann Vongkhamta took 6th in Creative expression
Erika Mork took 3rd in Prose
Morgan Pieper got an honorable mention in poetry and Jacob Rademacher got one in Drama.

The teams best best category was duo. ALL of the pairs that we brought got awards on Saturday.

Drew Castillo and Rubyann took 6th place, Jacob Rademacher and Kailey Twiest took 3rd and Wyatt Borst and Ellie Coffel got 1st place in duo at their first meet!

post_text:
Congratulations to 7th graders Isabella Miller and Lacey Buckentin for winning the Congressional App Challenge for MN Congressional District 6 for 2019!

Their app called Think Smart is an app for kids to use that either struggle with school work or want to avoid the summer slide by challenging themselves.

They will be recognized nationally for their work and their app will be displayed in Washington DC in the US Capitol Building in March for #HouseofCode.

post_text:
6th grade science has been studying simple machines for the last two weeks. They have been talking about the mechanical advantage of using simple machines to make work easier to do.

Each hour class has a task that they need to perform with the building of a Rube Goldberg machine using three simple machines for each of the groups. The groups have to work together with the group in front of them and also the group behind them. The tasks include shooting a basketball, throwing a baseball, and recycling a piece of paper.

Winter Formal Announcement!

'Winter Wonderland' Theme

You will need to SIGN UP for the Winter Formal dance by WEDNESDAY January 15th!! Sign up sheets will be placed in the high school office and in Mrs. Hammer's room.

Cost is $10 to prepay and $15 at the door! (If we have less than 40 people signed up by January 15th, we will be cancelling the dance - so SIGN UP!)

If you are wanting to have a student from another school join you at the dance, you must talk to Mrs. Hammers IN ADVANCE.

Remember to sign up by Wednesday, Jan. 15th! We look forward to seeing you 'bust-a-move' at the Winter Wonderland Formal!

**MIDDLE SCHOOL HOLIDAY SPIRIT DRESS UP THEME:

Thursday 12/19/2019- “Colors of the Season Day!”
Wear colors that reflect the holiday season: red, green, white, blue, purple, silver, gold. Show off your holiday colors!

Friday 12/20/2019- “Favorite Holiday Character Day!”
Dress as your favorite holiday character: Frosty, Rudolph, Santa, Olaf, Jack Frost, Abominable Snowman, Buddy the Elf, The Grinch, Ralphie from “A Christmas Story”, Ebeneezer Scrooge…………and the list goes on.

Airplane Toss papers will also be sold at this time. $.50 apiece or 3 for $1.

post_text:
2019 Ag Career Fair

Central Schools is holding a career fair on Friday December 13 from 8-10 am.

This event will focus on careers in many areas of Ag and Ag-related industries. Representatives from companies specializing in manufacturing, machining, construction, and more will be on-hand.

The goal of this event is to inform students about all of the great career opportunities available to them in the future. Students will also see many applications of science and technology that they hadn't previously been aware of.

Parents are welcome to attend this event as well. Come be a part of this exciting event.

Currently, a lineup of nearly 30 tables of industry reps and college reps will be on-hand. The list of confirmed reps is growing as well.

For more information, contact Mr. Mesik at 952-467-7145 or jmesik@central.k12.mn.us

Why Eat School Breakfast?
School Breakfast really is the most important meal of the day for kids as it provides the necessary fuel to start a day of learning and achievement.

Research has shown that children who eat breakfast have:
~Higher Academic Scores
~Improved behavior
~Reduced tardiness and absenteeism
~Less visits to the Nurse’s Office

Fun Fact:
**ALL Kindergarten students are able to eat BREAKFAST FOR FREE! yes; that is correct; no applications; and NO CHARGE for ALL KINDERGARTEN Students who would like to eat breakfast at school!**
